","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England","Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, England":"Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1185–1265":"1185–1265","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1226–1266":"1226–1266","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1190":"1190","1315":"1315","1226":"1226","1266":"1266","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England","Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, England":"Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Picot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Francois, Jacques, Jeanpaul, Luc, Pascal, Yves.  Spanish Esperanza, Aida, Alicia, Ana, Felipe, Luis.","French: from Old French <i>picot</i> ‘pointed object, pickaxe’, a nickname for someone who used such an implement. This surname is also found in Haiti.","Catalan: nickname from Valencian dialect <i>picot</i> ‘(sheep or goat) bell’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pickett","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Picot</i>, <i>Pigot</i>, a pet form of <i>Pic</i> (see   Pike   6). In Middle English, the form <i>Piket</i> (Old French <i>Picquet</i>) was also common.","sometimes a late development of   Pickard   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Picotte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Honore, Andre, Jacques, Serge.","Altered form of French   Picot  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Peter Picot was born in 1185, in Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas Picot. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Muriel de Somery. He died in 1265, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1185–1265":"1185–1265","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1226–1266":"1226–1266","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1190":"1190","1315":"1315","1226":"1226","1266":"1266","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England","Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, England":"Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1185–1265":"1185–1265","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1226–1266":"1226–1266","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1190":"1190","1315":"1315","1226":"1226","1266":"1266","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England","Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, England":"Brampton Ash, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1185–1265":"1185–1265